segments.text: Testing, testing, testing.
January 21, testing, testing.
January 21, testing, 2-2-2.
This is Friday, the 21st of January, I believe, sitting in the office with David Brooks Cofer, Jr., known by everybody here in town as just Brooks, I believe.
And then test yours, sir.
All right, sir.
That's correct.
Here we are.
All right.
Normally when we begin these, I ask people to give a brief biographical summary.
But in this case, because you grew up on the campus, I hope that our interview will concentrate on your growing up in the campus community.
Let's begin by your recording on this machine for us, your recollections of your parents' background before they came to College Station.
Where did they grow up and where did they live?
because we want to get as much information we can about them on this tape.
All right, sir.

My father was a native Kentuckian, born in 1886, graduated from Center College at Danville, and then took a teaching job at a small school in Missouri, and then also another year teaching in Arkansas.
and got the opportunity to come to Texas A&M in 1909, and he reported for the 1910 session.
And of course, when he came, the problem of girls on the campus at A&M, he recognized that.
And his introduction to society, I guess, was to the Bryan 400.
of which my mother was a member.
She was Sarah Nancy Allen, the daughter of Mr. John Hodges Allen, the founder of Allen Academy.
So she was a native.
At that time, I think Allen Academy had been in Bryan for something like 20 years or something.
I don't know.
And so they met and became...
known to each other, and finally married in 1917.
Shortly thereafter, or the next year, I believe, my sister was born, and Papa and Mimi, that I called, were living on a campus at 125 Wood Street.
And then I came along in 1922, born in an old four-apartment
house on the corner across from the Duncan home and catty corner from Walton Hall, which is approximately before you get to the North Gate area off of the campus.
125 Wood Street was just two doors down on the same street in front of what is now called the Dixie Chicken.
Oh, that's a fast background.
But the apartment building where you were born was on the north side of, was it on the campus?
It was on the campus.
Oh, opposite where the Dixie Chicken is today.
Very close, you see, to the Northgate area and right across from the Duncan home that I knew.
who was the manager of the mess hall.
Back up in that, you mentioned the 400 in Bryan.
Well, that's what they've always been known as.
Even in my days going through high school and going through A&M, the local girls were known as the Bryan 400s.
Now, they varied from time to time due to the ages and the classes that they would go with at A&M.
So if you were known as going with the Bryan 400, that was one of the local girls.
All right.
Was any local girl in the 400, or was that supposedly a status symbol?
That was just a conglomerate.
I mean, that was just what they called them.
My sister was in that because she was College Station Bryan.
And they were known on the campus as the Bryan 400.
Can you recall and describe anything you remember having heard about how your dad linked up with A&M?
How did he and A&M know there was a possibility of his coming here?
As I understand it, his degree was in Latin.
And he ended up an English teacher, but he came as a Latin teacher, but he taught English.
Now, I can only, I can look in a file that I have.
I do have the letter of his offer to come, and I'll be glad to show you that off the record, you know, if you'd like to see that.
And he came, and as I recall it, it was...
He was offered a position for nine months at $1,000.
And so at that time, historically, I think there was a recession shortly after he got out of college, and that was a golden opportunity.
Now, his graduate work after center college was... Was at Wisconsin and Chicago.
He got his master's degree at the University of Wisconsin.
Okay.
He didn't have a doctoral degree, or did he?
No, sir, he did not have a doctoral degree.
And he came, I assume, on the railroad.
Have you heard any descriptions of what he brought with him?
Was it more than a suitcase?
In those days, travelers had trunks.
And I know he had a trunk because it stayed in the household for years and years after that.
But he came in a trunk, and of course, when he arrived at College Station, I've never heard him say much about it, but they had what they called the Shirley Hotel, which was a
bachelor club order where single instructors could stay.
And I think that's where he first stayed.
And that was located, I think, close to the Aggieland Inn, which doesn't exist, but in that same area.
That'd be kind of west of where the old Northgate Post Office is now.
It would be south towards, well, not far from the president's home.
You're right.
The one that burned.
The one that burned in that area, I think is where it was.
All right.
And so he teaches here then beginning in 1910 for the rest of his active career.
That's true.
And he retired in 1957.
As an archivist, that was his final position at A&M.
As far as you are aware, what course or courses did he most enjoy teaching?
Well, in those days, the English department was more or less, I don't know what academically they call it.
It was just a coincidental department for the study of agriculture and engineering.
And at that time, they had freshman English and they had sophomore English.
And then for the more advanced classes, they had report writing, public speaking, you see.
Well, that's all changed now.
But he was sophomore literature and sophomore English, I guess, were his main courses.
Did you ever hear him express his feelings about A&M and A&M students?
Well, he was quite known, I think, by the former students who would come back and make contact with him.
And he got a great deal of pleasure out of hearing from them when he became the archivist, because they would know about the old times and they would
contact him and express appreciation for what he was doing, trying to collect some history about the university.
And they also assisted him because at that time the archivist was underwritten more by the association of former students than it was the university.
So he had a great deal of contact with his former students like
Mr. J. Harold Dunn, who was on the board, as I recall, was one of them that he had a lot of contact with, and others.
Let me throw in an anecdote on J. Harold Dunn to get it recorded.
I happened to be the master of ceremonies when the Kruger Dunn dormitory complex was dedicated, and I learned that Mr. Dunn's wife had grown up in a little town named Garland.
where I lived until I was 10 and where my parents grew up.
And her name, if I'm not mistaken, her maiden name was Louise McCollum.
And I asked my dad if he had known a girl with that name.
He was sure.
She was almost related to us, you know, kind of second cousin once removed sort of.
I said, whatever happened to her dad?
He said, well, we kind of lost touch.
She married some little bitty guy and he went off to somewhere up in the panhandle.
I never heard of anything that he ever did.
And I said, well, let me tell you what Mr. J. Harold Dunn accomplished with the founding of what is now Shamrock Oil.
He did OK. Let's see.
Your dad was not the first archivist, was he?
Was either Papa Oz or Mr. Ernest Langford.
Oh, no, he precedes Mr.
So your dad was.
I believe he was, yes.
But Mr. Lankford did a very good job, too.
Oh, you bet.
As your memory begins, where did the English department office, where were... Third floor of the academic building.
Not the, well, that was the building, the academic building is the building with the dome, you see.
Yes, yes.
The administration building is further east, so built in the 30s.
But it was on the third floor of the academic building.
All right, now let's start with your memories.
You said you were born.
Of course, they tell me that, you see.
I guess my early memories begin when I was going to A&M Consolidated School.
It was a stucco building on the campus that later became a music hall, and it was right at the end of the Joe Routt Boulevard to the east.
There was a two-story stucco building there.
And immediately behind us was the pastures for the Animal Industries Department, and I
went to first grade through seventh grade there.
And then from the seventh grade, we went to high school.
We had no middle school, but we went up towards the academic building in an old dormitory called Pfeiffer Hall.
Pfeiffer Hall was between the academic building and the physics building.
So we were given that location for the high school.
And I attended there.
and finished in 1939, then went to A&M.
But the early recollections would be in grammar school there at, well, the old A&M Consolidated High School, I mean school.
As far as you recall, about how many first graders were there when you were a first grader?
Was it one room or two rooms?
A&M Consolidated at that time,
had students coming from the rural communities, like Wellborn.
And then down close to Wellborn was Men of Springs.
They came from all over.
That's why it was consolidated.
But in our class, we'd have 25 students.
So was there one teacher full-time for the first grade?
That's correct.
And her name was Ms. Fred L. Sloop.
S-L-O-O-P. S-L-O-O-P. Was she, by chance, a faculty wife?
No.
I think her husband, as best I recall, was a teacher in the Bryan school system.
And she taught out at Consolidated and was known for the Sloop method of...
learning to read.
It was a phonetic system.
And that's what she was famous for.

Now, of your, of those years that you were in first through 11 grades, for someone your and my age, we weren't in 12th grade system yet, about what percentage were faculty kids, faculty and staff kids?
Half.
I would say that's a fair estimate.
Of course, you know, they weren't maybe from the faculty homes, but there were a lot of auxiliary homes and families that were connected with the college, like the Building and Grounds Department.
They provided any number of

houses on the campus for those positions, like the head of the power plant, Mr. Mousner, had children going to, and the other employees of the buildings and ground department had children that also went, you see.
So there were any number, but a great deal
of them came from the rural outlying areas.
Now, as your memory begins, kindergarten or first grade?
No kindergarten.
We went to the first grade, no kindergarten.
Where did you all live as your first grader?
We lived at 125 Wood Street, which was right in front of Walton Hall.
And I would walk to school.
And I would come home at lunch for a noon meal and go back to school walking and then come home in the afternoon.
What did you and your friends do for fun?
For fun.
Describe the play activities of youngsters.
Well, we had to make up fun sometimes.
Like I remember in the summer time,
Our next door neighbor was Mr. J.W.
Mitchell in the math department.

And he was a great entertainer, but he also would set up a game of washers where we could participate and we would challenge each other and then we would pass the cup around as each victor was determined.
And I remember joining with me in that activity was John Sancet, who lived just down below us in what we call the pecan orchard.
His father was in the CE department.
And in the summertime, while we would have these
washer matches and challenge each other and then let Mr. Mitchell also participate in it with us.
Now we had a great deal of time, fun doing that.
I remember John was able to drive sooner than I was able to drive and his family had a car and on some Saturday afternoons while we would take 25 to 50 cents to go to town to see the movies.
But there was always something that if it weren't organized that we would find time to do.
Who were, in elementary school, who were your closest friends?
I guess the closest friend that our family had was the C.B.
Camel family.
Dr. Camel was taught modern languages, and he was my age, and we went to the same
Union Sunday School in the bottom of Gahn Hall, and naturally we went to a consolidated school.
And his sister was the same age as my older sister, so we were families and were always very familiar with them.
They lived on the
south side of the campus off of the drill field between the road to the old post office and Kyle Field.
There's a block there of campus housing.
And they lived in that area and in the back of them were the tennis courts that they were built for the students.
So I would say that
C.B.
Campbell, Jr., F.W.
Hensel, Jr., who lived just up the street from him, was a little older than we were.
But in my particular age group, there was Margaret Ann Williams, Dr. D.W. Williams' daughter.
Then there was Lucille Thornton, who married Allen Maidley and lived around the corner from them.
Virginia Jones lived on the same block there.
And then the Winklers lived not far around the corner.
We were all a group that went through grade school together and high school.
What were the social activities of your parents and their friends, what were their social activities on the campus or in the neighborhood?
I guess the main social activity was in the summertime when you would be sitting out on the lawn, somebody would walk by and come in and visit with you.
We didn't have air conditioning in those days, but that was the way to kind of cool off before nightfall.
And Mr. A. Mitchell around the corner
or anybody, Mr. Marburger.
Mr. Marburger was the greatest storyteller that ever hit A&M campus.
And he was head of the buildings and grounds.
And it was really fun to listen to the stories that he would tell.
I can't remember, but he was a great storyteller.
Did these stories have any common theme?
They were just stories of his activity and experiences that he had.
But he was a great storyteller.
His daughter
Billy May Marburger, oh, now, what can I think of?
Still lives around.
And she lived, they lived over not far from the entrance to Kyle Field, in that other block, immediately where the MSC is now, in that block.
That was solid campus housing in those days.
And they lived there.
But I can remember it was always funny and enjoyable for me to sit and listen to those stories.
They had a faculty club, as I recall.
They had dinners every so often.
And I think they may have had faculty dances in the mess hall, but I don't think my parents participated much.
What about bridge clubs?
They had a bridge club, the Little Bridge Club, they called it, that was made up of 12 ladies.
And as I recall, they didn't play for points.

But, well, they did play for points, but they wouldn't play for any kind of nickel or dime on the side, but they would figure it up at the end of the season who was the winner and so forth, and they'd pass the book to that person or something, as I recall.
But in that membership were Mrs. Camel, Mrs. Hensel, Mrs. Emmy Marstella,
Mrs. Ruth Harrington was a member, and Mrs. Echols was a member, and Mrs. Abbott, my mother, and they had 12.
And if they had a vacancy, there was a selection process, you know, that they had to meet the approval.
Were there any unwritten rules about social life?
For example, could you serve alcoholic beverages at a private party?
You know, I don't recall our ever having that at home when we lived on the campus.
But as I recall, it was more or less non-alcoholic.
And also, did the men ever play poker?
I don't recall.
I'm sure they must have had.
I know the students had poker games.
But you don't remember?
But I don't know whether the faculty, but I can imagine some of them,
sometime had some gatherings.
Fred Benson once told me a long time ago that one of the unwritten rules when he first arrived here he thought was never get involved in a divorce.
If you have a divorce then resign and go somewhere else.
I think that may have been the rule of thumb.
And he also said that one of the unwritten rules that he understood was
never serve wine or any other alcoholic beverage with the curtains open.
Yes.
I think that's right.

The only time you saw any kind of alcohol was at a football game, because they would be out-of-town spectators that would come in, and they would come from Houston, Dallas, Austin, so forth, and they brought their own.
And I remember when I would go through the stadium after a ball game, you could see the effect of there.
Let's see.
Back to your days as a youngster, did you and your buddies ever attempt any pranks on campus when you were in elementary or high school?
Pranks were played on us.
we'd have tricycles or wagons that would be in the front yard.
And then on April Fool's Day, we would find them perched up in the live oak trees in the front yard.
And they were put there by, we know, students looking for a prank to play.
But that happened all the time.
Of course, the students, everything revolved around
campus life, I mean, and the students were the main, well, they were the main source of fun or entertainment that you could have.
They had All Fools Day on April the 1st, where they would dress up and go to class in really outrageous costumes.
But that was a custom that I think ended during Colonel Moore's tenure as commandant.
And I think it terminated when he said, all right, we will have a review of a cadet corps at 11 AM.
And at 1 o'clock, you'll be back in uniform.
And that was the end of it.
Now, when that happened, it must have been in the middle 30s sometime.
For you as a youngster before you are an A&M student,

there must have been some kind of no-nos that you and your buddies knew, like did you all would not walk down the hallway of an A&M academic building while classes were underway, I presume, and that sort of thing.
No, that was the only limitation that I knew about was that I was never given permission to go in the dormitory.
Oh, okay.
I could never go into the dormitory.
And...
There was quite an occasion when school was out, when the term was out, that various people would go in and see what could be salvaged from what was thrown away by the students who had left.
But the only thing that was really of any value made was the coat hangers that they had to take back over to the North Gate Cleaners to get some little compensation.
So you don't remember any treasure that somebody found?
I do not recall any.
Let's see, you must have had a bicycle.
When did you get a bicycle?
I had a bicycle, and I can, you know, I remember, it's just like getting the scratch on, the first scratch you get on your new car, you're going to have some spokes that get broken in a bicycle.
And at that time,
Well, at a later time in high school, it was, I was able to be the special delivery messenger for the United States Post Office.
The special delivery letters would come in, and you would then deliver them at nine cents a letter.
And I used my bicycle to deliver those around the campus to students and to the offices.
That was during the summer months.
And at that time, the post office was a very small building close to where the Grove is now.
At the end of a street coming down from the MSC, there was a post office building there.
And of course, the later one was at the north gate.
So that old post office was not very far from the college station.
It was on the railroad.
It appeared to be on the railroad right of way of the Missouri Pacific.
The Missouri Pacific was closer to the campus than the Southern Pacific.
was west, but they paralleled each other.
With your special delivery duties, what would have been the normal number of special delivery letters?
It depended upon the time.
If somebody wanted to come to A&M and was late towards the end of the summer, they were getting in transcripts to the registrar's office.
So I would have any number of deliveries there.
Sometimes when there was a former short course, you know, they used to have those, there would be quite a number.
But sometimes you might not have over, from overnight mail, you might not have more than a half a dozen letters to deliver the next morning.
All right, with all of that huge amount of cash then you made at nine cents a letter, what did you normally spend that on?
Well, that's hard to say.
Actually, it didn't amount to much, but it amounted to something, and you just extended it over into the school year for school purposes.
Let's see, a church in those days, where did the churches were at the North Gate, except the Presbyterian, A&M Presbyterian Church met in the Y Chapel.
